THE DANICA CONFRONTATION
This is the emotional centerpiece of the session. Everything else ΓÇö Maven, Grelod, the lore ΓÇö is secondary. The players came to Riften expecting a plague. They found a breakup. But the loss of Kyboh changes the math on both sides.
FINDING DANICA
Danica is at the Temple of Mara, helping with the ongoing recovery effort ΓÇö tending to the last patients, blessing the memorial, organizing supplies for families who lost breadwinners. She is not hiding. She is not waiting for Davinia. She is WORKING.
When the party arrives at the temple, they see her before she sees them. She is kneeling beside an elderly man, hands glowing with restoration magic, speaking softly. She looks different ΓÇö thinner, tired, visibly aged by the purification ritual, but with a calm authority she didn't have before. Her posture has changed. She carries herself like someone who has done something impossible and knows it.
Krusp Fanck is standing near the temple entrance. Arms folded. Watchful. He is her shadow ΓÇö not controlling, not hovering, just PRESENT. The anti-Davinia.
KRUSP SEES THE PARTY
He sees them before Danica does. His reaction is immediate and controlled:
His jaw tightens. His hand moves to Dawnbringer's hilt ΓÇö not drawing, but touching. A reflex. The last time he saw these people, he called them monsters and walked away.
Then he counts heads. His eyes narrow.
He does not attack. He does not shout. He steps between the party and Danica ΓÇö not blocking, but positioning.
If the party approaches: Krusp speaks first. Low. Controlled. To Davinia specifically.
"She doesn't know you're here. Give her the choice. Don't ambush her with this."
A beat. Then, quieter:
"Where's the Khajiit?"
He noticed. The party's answer ΓÇö or their silence ΓÇö will tell him more than words.
DANICA TURNS AROUND
She finishes with her patient. She stands. She turns.
She has rehearsed this moment. She has six points prepared. She has Krusp behind her. She is ready.
Then she sees the group. And she counts.
"Where's Kyboh?"
She asks it before anything else. Before the anger. Before the speech. Before the boundaries. She looks at Davinia, then at the space next to Davinia where a loud, stupid, kind Khajiit should be standing. Her hand moves involuntarily to her pocket ΓÇö where the note is. Where the paw print is.
Let the party explain. However they choose. The truth: Hjolmar took him. The Matrix was a trap. Kyboh is gone. They don't know if he's alive.
HOW THE ABSENCE CHANGES THE ROOM
Danica prepared for a confrontation with people who abandoned her to go play hero. Instead she's looking at people who went to save their friend and lost him. Her six points are still valid ΓÇö everything Davinia did at Korvanjund still happened. But the moral high ground she built her speech on has shifted.
"You chose a dungeon over me" is true. But the dungeon cost them something real. They didn't come back triumphant. They came back diminished.
Danica's anger doesn't disappear. It reorganizes. The wall she built with Krusp's help is still there. But there's a crack in it now, and the crack is shaped like a paw print.
THE CONFRONTATION
This scene is still entirely player-driven. The GM plays Danica honestly. But her emotional state is different from the version where Kyboh is alive and the party rolls in at full strength.
DANICA'S EMOTIONAL STATE (REVISED): She is angry AND worried. The anger is about Davinia. The worry is about Kyboh. These two feelings are fighting each other in real time. She prepared a clean, surgical speech. Kyboh's absence has made it messy.
She still has her points. She still delivers them. But between the points, she keeps glancing at the empty space. The speech she rehearsed with Krusp was for a different version of this moment.
WHAT DANICA HAS PREPARED TO SAY
She will not scream. She will not cry (at first). She will be measured, clear, and devastating. Krusp taught her that boundaries are stated, not begged for.
Point 1 ΓÇö The Hands: "You held my face. I reached for your hands. And you slapped them away. Do you understand what that felt like? I was reaching for you and you HIT me."
She starts with the physical act because it's inarguable.
Point 2 ΓÇö The Dismissal: "Then you told me to leave. Not 'I need space.' Not 'Give me a day.' You said 'I need you to go.' In the middle of Korvanjund. In a snowstorm. You sent me into the wilderness alone because YOU were afraid."
Point 3 ΓÇö The Note: "And then the note."
She pulls it out. She has it. Five days of carrying it. But when she unfolds it, her eyes catch the paw print at the bottom. Her voice falters. Just for a second. She pushes through.
"You compared yourself to your father. The man who shipped you away and called it chess. And then you did the same thing to me."
"You said 'I need you, Danica.' You said 'every step you took away was a dagger in my heart.' But YOU made me take those steps. You SENT me away."
She looks at the paw print again. Her jaw tightens.
"Kyboh signed this. His little paw print. He was the only one who made me feel like the group actually wanted me around. And now he's gone."
Point 4 ΓÇö The Pattern: "You decide things for people. You decided I couldn't handle what was happening to you. You decided Korvanjund was too dangerous for me. You decided I should go to Riften. You decided the Crown was your burden to carry alone."
"And every time you decide FOR someone, you tell yourself it's love. It's not, Davinia. It's control."
Point 5 ΓÇö What She Found: "I am not leaving the Lanterns because I hate you. I am leaving because I am a better healer, a better priestess, and a better person when I am not waiting for you to decide what's best for me."
"I saved this city. I saved Hemming Black-Briar. I performed a ritual that nearly killed me. And I did it without you."
Point 6 ΓÇö The Door: "If you want me in your life ΓÇö not as a piece you move around the board, not as someone you send away when things get scary, but as an equal ΓÇö then prove it. Not with notes. Not with symbols. With being here. With staying."
"But I will never again let you hold my face with the same hands that slapped mine away."
THE CRACK ΓÇö KYBOH'S ABSENCE AS THE TURNING POINT
After the six points land, there is silence. Danica delivered her speech. She held together. She did what Krusp taught her.
But she's looking at four people instead of five. And the speech she prepared assumed she was cutting ties with a group that was whole, that was powerful, that didn't need her. That's not what's standing in front of her.
This is where Davinia has a path back. Not through arguing the points. Not through defending her actions. Not through explaining the Crown or the danger. Every one of those responses will hit Danica's prepared walls and bounce off.
The path is through the loss.
If Davinia talks about Kyboh ΓÇö not strategically, not to guilt Danica, but because she is genuinely grieving and Danica is the one person outside the party who loved him too ΓÇö the wall cracks.
If Davinia says something like: "I know I did all of those things. You're right about every one of them. I can't undo any of it. But Kyboh is gone and I couldn't stop it and I don't know if he's alive and I am asking you ΓÇö not telling you, ASKING ΓÇö please don't leave too."
That's the key. ASKING instead of TELLING. The entire speech Danica prepared was about Davinia deciding things for people. If Davinia, for the first time, genuinely asks instead of decides ΓÇö if she puts the choice entirely in Danica's hands with no manipulation, no poetry, no framing ΓÇö Danica's wall breaks. Not because of guilt. Because the pattern just changed.
PLAYER RESPONSES ΓÇö GM GUIDANCE
If Davinia is vulnerable about Kyboh AND accepts the criticism: This is the best case. Danica's lip trembles. She looks at the paw print. She looks at Davinia. She is fighting between the boundary she set and the grief she shares.
She says: "You're going to get him back?"
If Davinia says yes ΓÇö or says she doesn't know but she's going to try:
"Then I'm coming with you. Not for you. For him. And because someone needs to keep you alive long enough to find him."
She folds the note and puts it away. She doesn't hug Davinia. She doesn't say "I forgive you." But she's coming.
Her terms: She is a Lantern again, but the dynamic has changed. She is not Davinia's dependent. She is not the person who waits to be told what to do. She will challenge Davinia's decisions. She will say no. She will set boundaries in real time. And if Davinia slaps her hands away again, she will leave and she will not come back.
If Davinia apologizes but stays defensive about the Crown / the reasons: Danica softens but doesn't break. She says: "I hear you. I believe you're sorry. But you're still explaining. Come back when you can just say 'I was wrong' without a 'but.'" ΓÇö She stays in Riften. The door is open but she doesn't walk through it yet. She might rejoin in a future session if Davinia demonstrates change.
If Davinia tries to use Kyboh's loss strategically ΓÇö as leverage rather than honest grief: Danica sees through it instantly. "Don't use him to get what you want. That's exactly what I'm talking about." Krusp shifts behind her. The wall holds.
If Davinia gets defensive or argues the points: Danica's eyes go hard. "You're doing it again. I'm telling you how I feel and you're explaining why I shouldn't feel that way." The wall holds. Danica stays in Riften.
If Davinia cries: Danica almost breaks. Her lip trembles. But she holds ΓÇö unless the crying is paired with honest accountability. Tears alone are the old pattern (Davinia's pain becomes the priority). Tears plus "you're right, I was wrong, I'm asking you to come back" is something new.
If another party member intervenes: Danica looks at them. "This is between me and Davinia. Please." If they persist, Krusp steps in: "You heard her." EXCEPTION: If another party member talks about Kyboh ΓÇö about what happened in the dungeon, about the loss ΓÇö Danica listens. She cares about the group even if she's furious at its leader.
If Davinia asks about the money: Danica: "I did the job. The Lanterns' job. I used the name because I was still a Lantern when I arrived. The gold is in my room at the Bee and Barb. All of it. I don't want your money. I never did."
CROWN REACTION THROUGHOUT
Ismara is completely silent during this entire conversation. She knows ΓÇö with 4,000 years of strategic intelligence ΓÇö that speaking now would destroy everything. Any whisper, any nudge, any comfort would prove Krusp's point: that Davinia is not alone in her own head, and that the people around her are right to be afraid of what she's becoming.
If Davinia explicitly asks the Crown for advice: one word. Quiet. Almost tender.
"Listen."
KRUSP DURING THE CONFRONTATION
He stands near the temple entrance. He does not speak during the confrontation unless addressed directly. He does not touch Danica, guide her, or prompt her.
When Danica's wall cracks over Kyboh ΓÇö when her voice falters at the paw print ΓÇö Krusp's expression changes. Not softening toward Davinia. Concern for Danica. He is watching to see if this is genuine grief or manipulation. If it's genuine, he respects it. If it's manipulation, he'll say so.
If the party addresses Krusp directly:
He meets their eyes. His voice is flat, professional, and cold.
"I told you at Kynesgrove what I thought of you. Nothing I've seen since has changed my assessment. But this is her conversation, not mine."
If pressed about his relationship with Danica: "I am her friend. And I am the person who was here when you were not. That is all you need to know."
If anyone threatens Krusp: He doesn't flinch. "Try."
If Danica decides to go with the party: Krusp looks at her for a long time. He does not argue. He does not try to stop her. He nods once.
"You know where to find me if you need me."
He watches them leave. He does not follow. But he will be checking in. And if he hears Davinia hurt Danica again, he will come. Not as a mentor. As a force of nature.
AFTERMATH ΓÇö WHAT DANICA DECIDES
Best case (genuine vulnerability about Kyboh + accepting all criticism + asking not telling): Danica comes back. She joins the party. But on her terms. She is an equal now, not a dependent. She will challenge Davinia. She will say no. She will heal them because it's the right thing to do, not because Davinia told her to. The relationship between Davinia and Danica is NOT repaired ΓÇö it is RESET. Everything is rebuilt from zero. Trust is earned, not assumed.
Middle case (sincere apology but still defensive about reasons): Danica stays in Riften but the door is open. She says: "Prove it. Come back when you can say 'I was wrong' without explaining why you were right." She might rejoin in a future session if Davinia demonstrates actual change in her behaviour.
Worst case (defensive, manipulative, or controlling response): Danica says: "Then I think we're done." She turns back to her patient. Krusp stays between them and the temple. The conversation is over.
GM NOTE ON THIS SCENE: The party just lost a member to a real-world situation. Punishing the remaining players by permanently removing their healer over something they had no control over is not fair. The confrontation should be hard, honest, and emotionally real ΓÇö Danica's points are all valid and she delivers every one of them. But there needs to be a path home. The path is through genuine vulnerability about Kyboh's loss, paired with real accountability for what happened at Korvanjund. If Davinia's player can do both ΓÇö grieve honestly AND accept the criticism without defending ΓÇö Danica comes back. That's a high bar but it's a reachable one, and reaching it will feel earned.

MAVEN BLACK-BRIAR
THE AUDIENCE
Maven will summon the party once she learns they're in the city. She does not come to them. They come to her.
Location: The Bee and Barb, Maven's usual corner table. Two housecarls flank her. She's drinking Black-Briar Reserve ΓÇö the good stock, from the uncontaminated vats.
Maven's posture: Amused. Controlled. She considers the Lanterns useful allies ΓÇö they handled Thornheart Grove competently and their agent just saved her son.
"The Obsidian Lanterns. Back in my city. How nice."
If the party asks for payment:
Maven raises an eyebrow. A slight smile. Not cruel ΓÇö genuinely entertained.
"Your woman already collected. Ten thousand gold, my personal favour, and the Aegis. Rather efficient for a lone priestess, wouldn't you say? The contract was fulfilled by a member of your company bearing your name. I consider the debt settled."
If they argue: "I paid for results. I received results. If your internal accounting is in disarray, that is a personnel matter, not a financial one. I suggest you discuss it with your priestess."
What Maven WILL offer:
She has a new problem. The Meadery infiltration revealed Dragon Cult operatives in her city. She wants them found and destroyed. She is willing to pay for intelligence.
"Someone poisoned my Meadery. Your friend Krusp handled the muscle, but the architects of this scheme are still out there. I want names. I want to know how they got into my operation. And I want to know who else they've compromised in the Rift."
She offers 5,000 gold for actionable intelligence on the Dragon Cult's Riften cell. This is a hook ΓÇö one the party may or may not pursue depending on their priorities.

GRELOD THE KIND ΓÇö ORION'S CONTRACT
THE PUBLIC FACE
Grelod is visible in the city. The party will encounter her organically ΓÇö she's at the market buying food for the orphanage, she's at the temple donating blankets, she's giving a speech near the canal about "the resilience of Riften's children in these difficult times."
What the party sees: A small, elderly woman with kind eyes and a warm smile. She moves slowly, speaks softly, and every citizen she passes greets her with genuine affection. Children run up to hug her. Merchants give her discounts. Guards tip their helmets. She is the most beloved person in Riften.
What Orion needs to see: A target. Behind the grandmotherly warmth, behind the speeches and the hugs, is a woman the Brotherhood has been contracted to kill. The client ΓÇö an adult who grew up in her orphanage ΓÇö says she deserves to suffer.
THE INVESTIGATION
Orion cannot simply kill the most beloved woman in Riften without consequences. He needs to understand the target. Possible approaches:
Talk to the children: The orphans at Honorhall will say nothing negative about Grelod in public. They are TRAINED. If approached privately, with patience and the right approach (Guile TN 16 ΓÇö these kids have been conditioned), one might crack. What they reveal: the beatings. The starvation. The "training" ΓÇö hours of lockpicking practice, pickpocket drills, memorization of sewer maps. "Mother Grelod says good children are useful children."
Talk to Aventus Aretino: Aventus is in Riften. He can be found at the Bee and Barb, drinking alone, watching the orphanage from across the canal. He is an adult man with haunted eyes and scarred hands. If Orion identifies himself (carefully), Aventus will tell him everything. His childhood. The beatings. The "training." The children he left behind. The guilt that drove him to the Black Sacrament.
"She told us no one would believe us. She was right. She's still right. That's why I called you."
Observe the orphanage at night: After hours, the orphanage changes. Guile TN 14 to approach unseen. Through a window: Grelod's demeanour transforms. The kindly grandmother becomes something else entirely. Cold. Methodical. A child is practicing lockpicking on a series of increasingly difficult locks while Grelod watches with a stopwatch. Another child is being quizzed on sewer routes. A third is being punished ΓÇö standing in a corner holding heavy books at arm's length while Grelod eats dinner.
The Guild connection: If Orion investigates the Thieves Guild angle ΓÇö Brynjolf's operation ΓÇö he discovers the pipeline. Orphans graduate from Honorhall into Guild service. The best pickpockets, the quickest learners, the most psychologically broken (and therefore most obedient) children become Brynjolf's street-level assets. Grelod is not just an abuser. She is a factory.
THE CHECK-IN (Valerius's Order)
While Orion is resting in Riften, his thirst sated from the hunt, the Ring of the Pale Regent suddenly hums with a cold, dull pressure. Valerius Caelus speaks directly into his mind. It isn't a grand entrance; it's a brisk, administrative update.
Valerius: "The orphanage is an ideal intelligence hub. Children are invisible to adults, and they go everywhere. The old woman, Grelod, is a Thieves Guild asset ΓÇö too entrenched to turn. Kill her however your Brotherhood requires. But the assistant, Constance Michel, is a blank slate. I want her."
Valerius pauses, his tone shifting to a sharp, instructional warning.
Valerius: "Enthrall her. And Orion ΓÇö ensure you channel the binding through the Ring, not your own will. I know you are sated enough to manage it yourself by now, but the asset belongs to the Court, not you. Do not mix the channels. Put her on my leash, not yours."
THE REVELATION (The Blind Spot)
The connection closes. Orion is left standing in the silence, processing two massive pieces of information Valerius just accidentally handed him.
The Power: Orion didn't know he could enthrall people yet. Valerius's casual instruction just gave Orion the manual to his own advancing biology. As long as he is fully sated, he can dominate a mortal mind.


The Flaw: More importantly, Valerius assumed Orion already knew this. Valerius assumes Orion has been testing his limits. Which means Valerius isn't in his head 24/7. The Ring's surveillance is not absolute; it has blind spots. Valerius only knows what he tunes in to see, or what he logically extrapolates. The panopticon is flawed. Orion can hide things from him.


THE IMPOSSIBLE HIT & THE USURPER'S CHOICE
Orion is now caught in a brilliant, multi-layered puzzle.
The Kill: He must assassinate Grelod in a way that makes her suffer (to satisfy Aventus Aretino) but looks like a tragic accident or a localized disaster (so Maven Black-Briar doesn't lock down the city to protect her Guild pipeline).


The Enthrallment (The Choice): He must corner Constance Michel and take her mind. But now he knows he has a choice:


The Court's Tool: Channel the Ring. Constance becomes Valerius's spy. Orion obeys orders and keeps his cover perfectly intact.
The Usurper: Use his own newly discovered, innate vampire powers to enthrall Constance for himself. He gains a personal spy network in Riften, and because he now knows Valerius's surveillance isn't perfect, he might actually be able to hide his treason from the Ring.
The Maven complication: Maven protects Grelod because the orphanage is a critical asset. If Grelod dies, Maven loses her recruitment pipeline. If Maven discovers Orion killed her, the party's relationship with the most powerful woman in the Rift is destroyed.

OTHER THREADS IN RIFTEN
SAIJAH ΓÇö THE PREDATOR'S LENS
Because the party cleansed Thornheart Grove weeks ago, the Rift's root network is the healthiest in Skyrim. The crushing psychic migraine that plagued Saijah in the Pale fades to a dull, distant murmur.
But the absence of pain leaves room for something else to step in. Kynareth's voice is muffled by the stone walls of the city. Hircine, however, thrives in the dark, cramped alleys where predator and prey are locked in a cage together.
The Manifestation (The Free Trial): As Saijah descends into the shadows of the lower city (or the Ratway), a new sensation hits her. It is not a magical aura or a divine whisper. It is a sudden, terrifying biological clarity.
Her pupils dilate. She doesn't just see the dark; she cuts through it. The ambient noise of the city fades, replaced by the rhythmic, thumping sound of heartbeats through the stone walls. She can smell the stale sweat of the guards above. She can smell the sharp, metallic tang of fear from a mercenary hiding in the tunnels ahead.
Mechanic: Hircine did not ask permission. He has granted her a taste of the Alpha's senses. Functionally, nothing can hide from her, and she no longer needs sight for combat. She can track targets flawlessly by scent and heartbeat through walls and absolute darkness.
Ylva's Jealousy (The Rivalry): Ylva, walking nearby in the dark, stops. The werewolf's nostrils flare. She smells the change on Saijah ΓÇö the primal, undeniable scent of Hircine's favor.
Their first interaction was awkward; this one is territorial. Ylva steps too close, invading Saijah's space. Her usual boisterous grin is tight, her eyes flashing with genuine, bitter jealousy.
Ylva: "You smell them, don't you? The blood pumping in the dark." She scoffs, looking Saijah up and down with obvious disdain. "I don't get it. You weep over healthy trees and hesitate on the draw, but the Hunter is offering you the teeth anyway. He gave you the scent."
Ylva leans in, her voice dropping to a competitive, predatory growl.
Ylva: "You better not waste His gift, Elf. If He's letting you smell the blood, you'd better be the first one to spill it. If you're going to hesitate, get out of my way and let a real wolf eat."
The Payoff: This makes Hircine's offer a tangible, incredibly powerful physical sensation that Saijah has to actively manage. It also establishes a fierce, competitive rivalry with Ylva. Ylva will now actively try to out-hunt and out-kill Saijah in every combat encounter to prove to Hircine that she is the true apex predator of the pack, forcing Saijah to either compete or be left behind.
ALFONSO ΓÇö THE MEADERY (The Corrosive Communion)
The Investigation: Maven grants the party access to the sealed lower vats of the Black-Briar Meadery. It is treated like a hazardous bio-zone. Alfonso bypasses mundane alchemy and communes directly with the residual sludge.
He does not find his own work. He finds the work of a rival. The pathogen inside the vat is highly advanced, mathematical, and completely sterile. The cellular structure is rigid and engineered to feed specifically on Restoration magic. It lacks the hunger of Namira or the natural, chaotic cycle of Peryite. To Alfonso, this is soulless science trying to mimic divine pestilence. It is the work of a clinical, arrogant prodigy (Antoine) treating disease like a mechanism. It is a professional insult to Alfonso's art.
The Dead End: To stabilize this artificial plague, the creator used a highly specific binding agent. Alfonso's virology parses the chemical structure ΓÇö it's a floral toxin, but it doesn't exist in any modern alchemical text. It is extinct. Alfonso knows how it works, but not what it is or where it comes from.
The Transaction (The Rusting Blade): To get the answer, Alfonso must ask the Taskmaster. He draws his iron rapier ΓÇö his phylactery. He connects directly with Peryite, demanding to know the nature of the rot.
Peryite answers. The Daedric Prince of Natural Order is profoundly offended by Antoine's pathogen ΓÇö an artificial, sterile bioweapon that circumvents the natural cycle of life and decay. Peryite grants Alfonso the knowledge to hunt down this blasphemer, but channeling divine truth through a mortal, iron vessel carries a physical toll.
The Cost: The rust spreads visibly up the rapier. Flakes of dead iron fall away to the stone floor. Alfonso permanently sacrifices a fraction of his phylactery's structural integrity (his own lifespan) to buy the answer.
The Revelation & The Payoff: The knowledge drops into Alfonso's mind like a lead weight, absolute and undeniable:
The catalyst is the Tears of Rahgot. The Death-Bloom of the Last Redoubt. It grows in only one place in all of Mundus: the blood-soaked soil of Forelhost, the ancient Dragon Priest tomb high on the mountain peak directly south of this very city.
Result: Alfonso paid in rust, but he got the coordinates. He knows there is a Dragon Cult alchemist manufacturing sterile plagues in Forelhost. The party now has a direct target (Antoine and Rahgot) and a ticking clock.
(GM Note: Peryite gives the coordinates and the name, but no historical context. To survive breaching a Dragon Priest tomb, the party will need to ask their new Dragon Cult expert ΓÇö Esbern ΓÇö who can provide the terrifying historical context of Forelhost's mass suicide.)
KYBOH ΓÇö THE EMPTY CHAIR
He is not here. The party may visit places in Riften that remind them of the Thornheart Grove adventure ΓÇö the first mission they did together, when the group was whole. If they walk past Honorhall Orphanage, past the canal, past the Bee and Barb where Maven first hired them, they are walking through a city full of memories that include someone who is no longer with them.
GEAR does not understand why the party is grieving. If asked: "Primary Organic Designate Kyboh was translated to a fixed location via tonal recall. He is not 'lost.' His coordinates are known. The Singing Glacier. You could go there."
The simplicity of this statement ΓÇö "you could go there" ΓÇö is both helpful and agonizing. They COULD. But they can't. Not now. Not depleted. Not with three fires burning.

