The party has time in Riften. The Danica confrontation, Maven's audience, Orion's contract, and the personal threads above can fill one to two sessions of city play. But the world is not waiting for them. Three crises converge on Riften in the form of three separate arrivals ΓÇö not simultaneously, but over the course of their stay. Space them out. Let each one land.
HOOK A: THE QUARANTINE OF KINGS (Windhelm)
The Messenger: A young Stormcloak soldier, feverish, pale, visibly sick. One of Galmar's runners. He arrives at the Bee and Barb looking for the Lanterns. He's an active carrier ΓÇö sweating, coughing into a blood-stained rag, eyes wide with fever.
His Plea (Read aloud):
"Wardens... Lady Caelus. General Stone-Fist sent me. You have to come to Windhelm. The army... we're dying.
We never even breached the gates of Dawnstar. The sickness started on the march ΓÇö it came from Korvanjund, from the medical supplies. Half the First Cohort was dead in the snow before we drew swords. Vokun just watched us rot from the walls.
General Stone-Fist ordered the retreat, but we brought it back with us. The healers... their magic does nothing. The poultices just make it spread faster. The Grey Quarter is a mass grave and it's moving into the Valunstrad. Ulfric has sealed the Palace of the Kings. He won't let anyone in or out.
Galmar is holding the barricades, trying to keep the healthy separated from the sick. He said you faced the walking dead at the tomb. He said your magic was strong enough to hold them back. He begs you... if you have any honor left, help us find a cure before the rebellion dies in its own bile."
What the party knows ΓÇö the dramatic irony:
This is not a random plague. This is Alfonso's pathogen. He deliberately infected the Stormcloak medical supplies at Korvanjund. His bespoke Peryite/Namira synthesis ΓÇö designed to spread rapidly, rot the host, and feed on Restoration magic. The healers' poultices making it spread faster is confirmation: he built a disease that weaponizes the cure.
The party watched him do it. They know. The courier does not.
Galmar Stone-Fist ΓÇö the man Davinia lied to about the Jagged Crown ΓÇö is now begging her to save his army from a plague her own companion created.
The Dawnstar consequence: While the party was in Mzinchaleft, Galmar led the First Cohort north to liberate Dawnstar from Vokun's occupation. The infected medical supplies incubated during the freezing march. By the time they reached Dawnstar, the army was collapsing from within. Vokun didn't need to fight ΓÇö he watched the rebel army destroy itself from the walls. The retreat brought the plague back to Windhelm. Dawnstar is now a permanent, fortified Dragon Cult stronghold. The party's absence cost the Stormcloaks a city and an army.
Alfonso's opportunity: Windhelm is a live-fire laboratory for his masterwork. His prototype pathogen broke an entire army and is consuming a capital city. The Peryite cultist at Korvanjund gave him a password to a hidden shrine beneath the New Gnisis Cornerclub in Windhelm's Grey Quarter. The Afflicted Conclave has the theological scriptures Alfonso needs for his Vrykolas synthesis. He must navigate a quarantined, plague-ridden city to find them.
Orion's opportunity: Captain Hroki survived the retreat from Dawnstar and is trapped in the quarantined city, likely helping Galmar hold the barricades. A chaotic, desperate, dying city is the perfect environment for an assassination.
Davinia's burden: Galmar is begging her for help, believing her an honourable ally. She lied to him about the Crown. She knows (or suspects) Alfonso is responsible for the plague destroying his army.
HOOK B: THE BLEEDING MOUNTAIN (Ivarstead)
The Messenger: Klimmek, the old provisioner from Ivarstead. He is not a courier. He is a refugee. He bursts into the Bee and Barb on a different day than the Stormcloak courier ΓÇö space these out ΓÇö his face etched with terror, beard frosted with ice.
He does not look for the Wardens. He stumbles to the bar, gasping, and shouts to the whole room:
"Don't go up the mountain! The 7,000 Steps ΓÇö they're cursed! I was making my weekly delivery to High Hrothgar ΓÇö food, supplies, you know. I do it every week. But this time... the stones... they were bleeding! Black sap, like what they say is happening in the deep woods, weeping from the Waystones! And the air... it feels wrong. Like time is twisted. I saw men in grey robes walking the path, but they weren't the Masters. They had... faces of horn and fire."
He shudders, takes a long drink of ale from the innkeeper.
"I ran. I didn't make it to the monastery. I ran all the way here. Someone has to warn the Jarl. Someone has to tell the Greybeards that their mountain is being defiled!"
Klimmek does not ask the party for help. He is raising a general alarm. The party overhears and must decide if this is their problem.
Saijah's reaction: The moment Klimmek says "black sap," Saijah feels a violent psychic SPIKE. Sharp, localized, directional ΓÇö pointing southwest toward the Throat of the World. The contrast is jarring; the Rift beneath her feet is healthy, making the screaming rot from Ivarstead feel infinitely worse. She recognizes the description instantly. It's the same Dagonic corruption she felt from the Eldergleam roots ΓÇö the same sickness she's been tracking since Thornheart Grove, through Solitude, through every dying gildergreen along the way. The Dagon cult isn't just targeting trees. They're targeting the most sacred site in Skyrim.
What the party knows: The Greybeards are not asking for help. They are beings of immense power who can shake the world with their voices. If even THEY are being besieged on their own mountain, the Dagon cult is operating at a scale the party hasn't encountered yet. Master Arngeir is not afraid. He is likely engaged in something the party cannot yet comprehend. But the mountain path is compromised and Klimmek ΓÇö the one man who keeps the Greybeards fed ΓÇö can no longer reach them.
HOOK C: THE LAST BLADE (Esbern ΓÇö The Dead Drop)
The Arrival: This happens last. After the courier. After Klimmek. While the party is moving through the Riften market after the emotional fallout with Danica.
Read aloud:
"As you navigate the crowded market stalls, a filthy street urchin bumps hard into Davinia [or Orion]. Before you can react, the boy mumbles an apology and disappears into the crowd. You feel a heavy weight in your pocket that wasn't there a moment ago. It's a rusted iron key, wrapped tightly in a scrap of stained parchment. The handwriting is jagged, rushed, and frantic:
'You killed the beasts of Kynesgrove and the Pale. But the Golden Eagles took my shield in Riverwood, and now they are in the sewers looking for me. The World-Eater wakes. I know how to kill the black god. If they find me first, the world burns. The Warrens, bottom level. Use the key. Hurry.'"
The Descent (The Ratway Race): When the party goes down to the Ratway, it is not a peaceful walk. Esbern's paranoia is justified.
The Scene: A squad of 4 Thalmor-funded mercenaries (or plainclothes Justiciars) are already down there. The party hears splintering wood and screams echoing through the tunnels as the hit squad kicks down doors in the Warrens looking for Esbern.
The Action: The party must navigate a high-tension stealth/combat encounter in the claustrophobic sewers. They have to silently eliminate or brute-force their way through the hit squad to reach Esbern's heavily trapped, reinforced door before the mercenaries breach it.
The Meeting: Once they use the key and enter, they find Esbern barricaded in a cramped, map-covered research bunker. He is terrified but resolute.
Esbern's pitch: He is the last of the Blades. He has been hiding in this hole for thirty years. He knows Alduin has returned. He knows there is no Dragonborn ΓÇö the prophecy has failed. And he knows the party killed two dragons when no one else could.
He needs the Dragonstone ΓÇö a map of every dragon burial mound in Skyrim. It is in Bleak Falls Barrow, overlooking Riverwood. His last scout reported strange activity near the barrow ΓÇö Dragon Cult operatives and Thalmor patrols in the area. The scout has not returned.
"The Dragonstone is the key. Without it, we are fighting blind ΓÇö waiting for each dragon to find us instead of hunting them at their graves before they rise. I have spent thirty years preparing for this moment. I cannot go myself. The Thalmor will kill me on sight. You are the only people in Skyrim who have proven they can face a dragon and survive."
What this means: Esbern is offering them the main questline. The Dragonstone leads to the dragon burial mounds, which leads to preemptive strikes against resurrecting dragons, which leads to Alduin. This is the long game. But it requires going to Bleak Falls Barrow ΓÇö through Thalmor-controlled territory, into a dungeon that may have been compromised by the Dragon Cult.

THE CHOICE
Three fires. Three directions. They cannot do all three at once.
Windhelm: Alfonso's plague is eating the Stormcloak army alive. Galmar is begging for help from the people who caused it. Orion's Brotherhood target is trapped inside the quarantine. Alfonso's Peryite scripture is in the Grey Quarter. Davinia lied to Galmar about the Crown. Time-sensitive ΓÇö people are dying of something the party did.
Ivarstead: Cosmic horror. The Dagon cult attacking sacred ground. Saijah's arc. The root network. The Greybeards under siege. Escalating ΓÇö the corruption is spreading.
Bleak Falls Barrow: The main questline. Esbern. The Dragonstone. Thalmor. Dragon Cult. The key to fighting Alduin. Strategic ΓÇö not urgent today but critical for the future.
Let them argue. Let them weigh. Do not push them toward any hook. The choice they make defines the next arc.

GM NOTES ΓÇö RUNNING THIS MODULE
The emotional hit is the point. The party spent days in a dungeon solving Kyboh's problem. While they were gone, Danica solved Riften's problem without them. The Obsidian Lanterns are heroes in this city ΓÇö their name is on the wall. But the party members standing at the gate had nothing to do with it. The Lanterns' finest hour happened because the party wasn't there.
Danica's confrontation is not a cutscene. It is the most important roleplay of the arc. Give Davinia's player space to respond. Do not rush it. Do not resolve it neatly. Messy is correct.
Krusp is not the villain. He is a principled man who saw the party do monstrous things and drew a reasonable conclusion. He is also the man who was present when Davinia was absent. He did nothing wrong. The party may hate him for it.
Maven is a resource, not an enemy. She considers the Lanterns useful. She will remain their ally as long as they remain useful. The moment they threaten her interests (Grelod, the Guild, the Meadery), that changes.
Grelod is Orion's problem. Do not solve it for him. The investigation, the approach, the execution ΓÇö all player-driven. The module provides the setup: a beloved public figure who is secretly a monster, protected by the most powerful woman in the city, with a client who wants suffering and liberation, not just death. The Valerius check-in adds a fourth dimension: Orion now has to balance the Brotherhood's demands, Maven's protection of her asset, Aventus's desire for public reckoning, AND Valerius's order to enthrall Constance ΓÇö while deciding whether to obey his master or begin building his own power base.
The Disguise Check sets the tone. The party is a group of monsters walking into a human city. Bjorn's exasperation is comedic relief before the emotional weight of the Danica scene, but the mechanic has real teeth ΓÇö a failed Suspicion Check makes Orion's contract and Alfonso's investigation materially harder.
Saijah's Hircine thread is a seduction, not a corruption. Hircine didn't ask permission. The predator senses are intoxicating and functionally incredible ΓÇö but they come from a Daedric Prince, not Kynareth. Saijah must decide what she does with power she didn't choose. Ylva's jealousy adds competitive pressure: if Saijah won't use the gift, Ylva will make her feel like she's wasting it.
Alfonso's Meadery scene is a clock. Every time he channels Peryite through the rapier, it rusts. Every answer costs lifespan. The revelation about Forelhost gives the party a concrete target ΓÇö but getting there means breaching a Dragon Priest tomb. Connecting Alfonso's Forelhost lead to Esbern's Dragon Cult expertise is a natural bridge between threads.
The note is a weapon. Danica has it. She has memorized it. She will quote it. If Davinia's player doesn't remember writing it, the confrontation will hit harder ΓÇö their character's words, coming back at them through the mouth of the person they hurt.
Hook B carries the Dagon foreshadowing for this session. Saijah has been tracking the Eldergleam corruption since Thornheart Grove in Session 1 ΓÇö through the dying gildergreen in Solitude, through Varon's reports on the road, through every root she's touched. She doesn't need to rediscover it in the Rift. Instead, Klimmek's bleeding mountain is the escalation: the Dagon cult has moved from trees to the Throat of the World itself. When Gaelen begins his main assault on the Eldergleam (Session 21), the players should remember that the signs were everywhere ΓÇö they just kept getting worse.
Esbern's dead drop replaces the tavern entrance. A thirty-year fugitive from the Thalmor does not walk into a crowded inn and introduce himself. The dead drop, the key, and the Ratway race are consistent with his paranoia and give the party an action beat (clearing the mercenary squad) between the emotional weight of Danica and the strategic weight of the Three Fires.

